author: Agencia Reforma
title: Al fin pagan adeudos adeudos a residentes del ISSSTE en Saltillo – Periódico Zócalo | Noticias de Saltillo, Torreón, Piedras Negras, Monclova, Acuña
text:
Saltillo, Coah.- Después de una semana de trabajar bajo protesta, este jueves 04 de abril los 87 médicos residentes del Hospital de Alta Especialidad del ISSSTE Saltillo levantaron la asamblea y se reincorporaron a su trabajo habitual, luego de que por fin a todos les depositaron el pago de su beca.
Los doctores en formación que laboran en 18 centros hospitalarios del país , denunciaron a finales de marzo que el ISSSTE a nivel federal les adeudaba el pago de dos quincenas de trabajo, motivo por el que iniciaron movilizaciones y protestas que visibilizaron a través de redes sociales.
El 02 de abril, la Secretaría del Salud Federal y el ISSSTE a nivel Federal, informaron que se encontraban realizando labores para agilizar los trámites administrativos y así pagar el retroactivo correspondiente a los médicos residentes a nivel nacional.
En el caso de los médicos de Saltillo que cubren residencia en especialidades como medicina interna, traumatología y ortopedia, anestesiología, ginecología, pediatría, cirugía general, entre otras, comenzaron a laborar bajo protesta el 27 de marzo y desde entonces realizaron sus guardias y se concentraron en el Auditorio del Hospital.
A principios de semana solo 66 habían recibido el pago correspondiente, sin embargo, mantuvieron la asamblea hasta este jueves en espera de que se cubriera el pago de la beca a los 21 restantes.

title: Se suman a EU para entegar ayuda a Gaza
text:
Clasificado El Diario La mejor forma de comprar y vender - Visitar
Larnaca, Chipre .- Reino Unido, la Unión Europea y los Emiratos Árabes Unidos se unirán a Estados Unidos para abrir una ruta marítima para la ayuda humanitaria a Gaza, dijeron funcionarios este viernes.
Ursula von der Leyen, presidenta del órgano ejecutivo de la UE, y David Cameron, secretario de Asuntos Exteriores de Reino Unido, anunciaron su participación horas después de que el presidente Joe Biden esbozara un plan estadounidense para construir un muelle flotante temporal frente a la costa mediterránea de Gaza para apoyar el envío de alimentos, agua, medicinas y otras necesidades a civiles palestinos desesperados.
Von der Leyen dijo que el primer barco que transporta ayuda podría partir de Chipre, nación de la UE, hacia Gaza tan pronto como el viernes, y que le seguirán más el domingo.
"Estamos poniendo en marcha este corredor marítimo de Chipre juntos, la Unión Europea, los Emiratos Árabes Unidos y Estados Unidos", dijo tras visitar unas instalaciones en Larnaca, en Chipre.
"Ahora estamos muy cerca de abrir este corredor, esperemos que este sábado o domingo y estoy muy contenta de ver que hoy se pondrá en marcha un primer piloto".
Pero no quedó claro de inmediato cómo o dónde los buques descargarían su carga o cómo sería distribuida en medio de los bombardeos israelíes y los ataques de palestinos hambrientos a los camiones de ayuda.
'Absurda propuesta de Biden'
Un experto de la ONU criticó el viernes los esfuerzos de Estados Unidos para aumentar la ayuda humanitaria a Gaza, como los planes para un puerto temporal y los recientes lanzamientos aéreos, que calificó de métodos "absurdos" y "cínicos" siempre y cuando La ayuda militar a Israel continúa.
En medio de advertencias de una hambruna inminente, cinco meses después de iniciada la campaña de Israel contra el grupo palestino Hamas en Gaza, el Ejército estadounidense ha llevado a cabo lanzamientos aéreos de alimentos en Gaza y planea un puerto temporal para importaciones de ayuda en su costa mediterránea.
Los lanzamientos aéreos en particular "harán muy poco para aliviar el hambre y la desnutrición, y no harán nada para frenar la hambruna", dijo a los periodistas en Ginebra Michael Fakhri, relator especial de la ONU sobre el derecho a la alimentación.
Advirtió sobre el caos a medida que personas hambrientas compiten por suministros. En cuanto al puerto, dijo que nadie lo había pedido. Llamó a los métodos portuarios y aéreos de "último recurso".
"El momento en que los países utilizan lanzamientos aéreos y estos muelles marítimos suele ser, si no siempre, en situaciones en las que se quiere entregar ayuda humanitaria a territorio enemigo", dijo.

author: Dexter Tilo
title: Employees ready to break company policy just to use AI, report finds
text:
Blind faith in IT, unclear AI policies drive unsupervised AI use
More than half of employees in the United States will risk violating company policy to use artificial intelligence tools to make their job easier, according to a new report.
Findings from CalypsoAI's Insider AI Threat Report revealed 52% of employees admitted they would use use AI to ease workloads, even if it breached policy and a quarter have already used AI without checking if it's allowed.
More than a quarter also confessed they submitted proprietary company info so AI could complete a task (28%) and used AI to access sensitive data or documents (28%).
"Employees increasingly see AI as a tool for efficiency or leverage, not a shared risk," the report read.
The latest insight into the secretive use of AI follows a recent Cox Business survey of more than 1,000 Gen Z and Millennial employees in the US that found younger employees were hesitant to admit they use the technology because of fear of losing work.
Reasons for the unauthorised use could be vary from blind faith in leadership and confusion about company policies.
The report found that 84% of employees are somewhat or very confident that their company's CEO or IT team would be able to catch an AI-led breach, while frontline employees, 21% said their company's AI policies were unclear, so they use AI as they wish.
Being disconnected from the company's values may also be a factor, as 30% of frontline staff said they don't care about their company's AI policy and 37% said they won't feel guilty if they broke AI protocol.
If they couldn't use AI, 25% said they would quit their job.
Donnchadh Casey, CEO of CalypsoAI, warned that frontline employees' unsupervised use of AI should be a "wake-up call" for organisations.
"We know the inappropriate use of AI can be catastrophic for enterprises, and this isn't a future threat - it's already happening inside organisations today," Casey said in a statement.
The findings come in the wake of widespread adoption of AI tools, including AI agents, in workplaces.
Previous findings from Workday revealed that 82% of organisations are deploying AI agents to reduce employee workloads and set the company up for financial success.
But CalypsoAI's poll found that 38% of leaders have no idea what an AI agent is, with 10% not being able to tell the difference between an AI agent and a virtual employee.
"Leaders are green-lighting AI faster than they can explain it," Casey said in the report. "You can't govern what you don't understand, and that disconnect is now a top-tier enterprise risk."
According to the CEO, uncritical enthusiasm for technology can quickly unravel progress for organisations.
"Without the right awareness, blind eagerness will have detrimental impacts for enterprises when it comes to AI implementation," he said.
"Organisations need both technical controls and compliance, along with tools to educate employees and create a broader culture of respect for the power of AI."

Georgia Mother’s Legal Battle Highlights IVF Errors and Emotional Toll[1]A Georgia woman’s harrowing experience with a fertility clinic has sparked a national conversation about the risks and ethical considerations of in vitro fertilization (IVF) procedures. Krystena Murray, a 38-year-old woman from Georgia, filed a lawsuit against Coastal Fertility Specialists after giving birth to a child who was not biologically hers. This case serves as a cautionary tale for couples undergoing IVF treatments, underscoring the need for better regulations and oversight in the fertility industry.

 
 
<- Figure and figure caption should contain relevant images related to the news article, either the individual is suing or the ivf clinic or the part of the press release which is still mandatory but due to privacy concerns, no image is yet available.>

 


 
 
 Journey to Motherhood and Shocking Discovery[3]Krystena Murray had always dreamed of becoming a mother and, after undergoing IVF at Coastal Fertility Specialists, achieved her lifelong aspiration: welcoming a baby boy. However, the joyous moment turned into a nightmare when she realized that the baby, a beautiful and healthy African American infant, did not resemble her or the sperm donor, both of whom were white. Recalling the moment, Murray stated at a press conference announcing the lawsuit, “I was happy. I was a mom. He was beautiful and perfect, but it was also very clear something was wrong.”
 
 
 Genetic Test Confirms the Unimaginable 
Alarmed by the stark difference in appearance, Murray performed an at-home DNA test, which revealed a devastating truth: she was not biologically related to the child. Upon informing the fertility clinic, who promptly notified the biological parents. Murray recalls, “Despite the shock, I bonded deeply with the child. I breastfed him, took him to doctor’s appointments, and cared for him throughout months of uncertainty.”

The emotional toll was immense. While caring for the child, Murray wrestled with fundamental questions: if this wasn’t her biological son, did he belong to someone else?

 
 
 Legal Battle and Heartbreaking Separation 
Once the biological parents were identified, they pursued custody, compelling Murray’s legal team to advise her to relinquish custody. Despite her deep emotional attachment and desire to raise him, she ultimately relinquished custody to the biological parents. Perris & Layrun & Associates, who were handling her case stated “She had to agree to relinquish custody, and the court found that they had no grounds to refuse. Devastated, she could only recall – “My baby is not genetically mine – he doesn’t have my blood, he doesn’t have my eyes, but he is and will always be my son. That is how hard it was to give him up”

This instance also highlights the importance of prompt medical attention to mothers dealing with postnatal depression dealing with such emotional assault.

 
 
 Suit Against Coastal Fertility Specialists 
 
 “She carried, lovingly cared for and delivered a child to her only to be struck down nearly half a year later”

Her lawsuit alleges that the clinic was responsible for a grievous error, rendering her an “unwitting surrogate” and causing her immense emotional distress. According to Murray’s lawsuit, “The clinic’s negligence robbed her of the child she had nurtured in the womb, as well as cared for countless times after birth.”

 
Seeking justice, Murray’s legal team is hoping to set a precedent and hold the Coastal Fertility Specialists accountable for the overwhelming circumstances this mother xic]

 
 has had to face. This case should give rise to the subsequent cases that this can happen to other mothers. Sharing her story in the public domain she further mentioned, “I spent my entire life wanting to be a mom. My hope in sharing my story is that this will help prevent this from ever happening to anyone else trying to start a family of their own”.
